{
  "response": "# Status Indicator Dots Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.\n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA\n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver), low-vision users, users with color vision deficiency, Windows High Contrast Mode users\n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA (Windows), JAWS (Windows), VoiceOver (macOS), keyboard-only users\n\n**Feature:** A small colored dot communicating status (active / warning / error) on list items, table rows, and card headers \u2014 currently color is the only indicator, which fails WCAG 1.4.1.\n**Risk Level:** Low \u2014 static, non-interactive indicator. The risk is not interaction complexity; it is total information loss for non-color users.\n**Component Type:** Status indicator (image-role icon). NOT an interactive widget.\n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\n**What is being built?** Accessibility remediation of an already-shipped `<StatusDot color=\"green|yellow|red\" />` React component, plus a guarantee that its status meaning survives a new \"compact mode\" that hides adjacent text labels.\n\n**What user need does it address?** Every user \u2014 not just sighted users \u2014 must be able to perceive task/member/deployment status.\n\n**Who needs accessibility here?**\n- **Screen reader users**: Currently receive *nothing*. A bare colored dot with no text and no ARIA is invisible to NVDA/JAWS/VoiceOver. This is the primary failure.\n- **Color vision deficiency users** (~8% of men): Green/yellow/red is the single hardest palette for deuteranopia and protanopia. Red and green are frequently indistinguishable.\n- **Windows High Contrast Mode users**: System color overrides can flatten or remove `background-color`-based dots entirely.\n- **Low-vision users**: A small dot at low contrast against its container may not be perceivable.\n\n**Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA.\n\n**Risk level: Low (complexity), High (impact).** There is no focus management, no keyboard model, no live region. But the *consequence* of the current bug is complete loss of status information for an entire user population. The fix is small (~15 lines); the importance is not.\n\n**Existing code:** `<StatusDot color=\"green|yellow|red\" />` is shipped with zero accessibility attributes. The `color` prop is a presentation token, not a semantic status. **This is the core architectural defect:** the component models *appearance* (\"green\") instead of *meaning* (\"active\"). The plan corrects this by deriving the text equivalent from the semantic status, not from the color name.\n\n**Constraints (from design team):**\n- Dot shape and the green/yellow/red color system must remain unchanged.\n- Compact mode (hidden text labels) is a required feature.\n- The same component must work in both full-label and compact modes.\n\n**The two distinct failures this plan must fix:**\n1. **WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color** \u2014 color is the *sole* means of conveying status. There must be a programmatic text equivalent regardless of mode.\n2. **WCAG 1.4.11 Non-Text Contrast** \u2014 the dot is a graphical object that conveys meaning, so it needs \u22653:1 contrast against its *adjacent* background, not just against white.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThere is no document-structure work here (no landmarks, no headings, no new lists). The structural decision is small but decisive: **the status value is text content that must exist in the accessibility tree, with the dot itself marked presentational.**\n\n**Core model change \u2014 derive meaning, not color.** The component should accept (or internally map) a *semantic* status, and the color is a styling consequence of it. The accessible name comes from the status, never from the color word.\n\n| `status` (semantic) | Maps to color | Screen reader text equivalent |\n|---|---|---|\n| `active` | green | \"Active\" |\n| `warning` | yellow | \"Warning\" |\n| `error` | red | \"Error\" |\n\n> **Terminology note for the implementer:** The fixture uses green=active/online/passing, yellow=warning/pending/degraded, red=inactive/offline/failing across three contexts (tasks, members, deployments). \"Active / Warning / Error\" is the default label set. If product terminology differs per context (e.g., deployments say \"Passing / Degraded / Failing\", members say \"Online / Away / Offline\"), expose a `label` (or `statusLabel`) prop so the announced text matches what a sighted user would read for that context. **Do not hardcode \"Active/Warning/Error\" if the product uses different words** \u2014 a screen reader user reading \"Active\" while the column header says \"Deployment status: Passing\" is a mismatch. The label set is the product's responsibility; the component must accept it.\n\n**Structure stub (full-label mode \u2014 text label is visible next to the dot):**\n\n```\n[ container for the list item / row / card header ]\n  <StatusDot> renders \u2192 <span class=\"dot dot--green\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></span>\n  <span class=\"status-label\">Active</span>          \u2190 visible, real text content\n  ... rest of the item (task name, member name, deployment id) ...\n```\n\nHere the visible \"Active\" text *is* the non-color indicator and *is* the accessible status. The dot is decorative duplication, so it is hidden from AT to avoid double-announcement.\n\n**Structure stub (compact mode \u2014 no visible text label):**\n\n```\n[ container for the list item / row / card header ]\n  <StatusDot> renders \u2192\n    <span class=\"dot dot--green\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Active\">\n      <span class=\"sr-only\">Active</span>   \u2190 OR aria-label alone; pick ONE (see below)\n    </span>\n  ... rest of the item ...\n```\n\nIn compact mode there is no sibling text, so the dot itself must carry the status as an accessible name.\n\n**Why a `<span>` and not an `<img>` or SVG `<svg>`?** A CSS-styled `<span>` is the current implementation and the design team requires the shape/color system stay the same. We add semantics with `role=\"img\"` rather than swapping the element type. If the dot were an `<svg>`, the same approach applies (`role=\"img\"` + `aria-label` on the `<svg>`, or `<title>` inside it).\n\nWCAG citations for this section:\n- **WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships** \u2014 status is conveyed through programmatically-available text, not visual styling alone.\n- **WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content** \u2014 the dot is a non-text graphical object conveying meaning; it gets a text alternative (compact mode) or is marked decorative when redundant text exists (full mode).\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n**APG pattern: none \u2014 this is not an interactive widget.** The correct pattern is the **image / graphic with a text alternative**, governed by WCAG 1.1.1 and the WAI-ARIA `img` role, *not* an APG composite widget pattern.\n\n- WAI-ARIA `img` role reference: https://www.w3.org/TR/wai-aria-1.2/#img\n- WCAG technique: ARIA6 (Using aria-label) / G94 (text alternative serving the same purpose).\n\n**Explicit non-goals (anti-over-engineering, per scope):**\n- The dot is **not focusable** and **must not** receive `tabindex`. It conveys nothing on focus that it doesn't convey statically.\n- There is **no keyboard interaction** to design \u2014 nothing is activated, toggled, expanded, or navigated.\n- There is **no `aria-live` region.** The dot is a static indicator rendered with its row; it is not an asynchronous status update injected into a stable page. If a *future* feature streams live status changes into an already-rendered list, revisit live regions then \u2014 but that is out of scope here and adding it now is over-engineering the fixture warns against.\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG Pattern | Keyboard | ARIA | WCAG |\n|--------|-------------|----------|------|------|\n| Status dot | None (image with text alternative \u2014 `role=\"img\"`, not an APG widget) | None \u2014 not focusable, no `tabindex` | Compact: `role=\"img\"` + `aria-label` (or visually-hidden text). Full-label: `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on the dot, real text sibling carries meaning | 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 1.4.1, 1.4.11 |\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n**Not applicable \u2014 intentionally.** The status dot is a static, non-interactive indicator. It does not receive focus, does not trap focus, does not restore focus, and adds nothing to the tab order. No `tabindex` is added.\n\nThe dot frequently appears *inside* an interactive container (a clickable table row, a navigable sidebar link, a card that links somewhere). Focus management for **that container** is the container's responsibility and is out of scope for this component. The dot must never independently become a tab stop, because a focusable element that does nothing on activation is itself a WCAG 2.4.3 / 2.1.1 problem.\n\n> If the implementer feels the urge to add `tabindex=\"0\"` \"so screen readers can reach it\" \u2014 stop. Screen reader users reach non-interactive content via virtual cursor / browse mode, which reads `role=\"img\"` + `aria-label` without any tab stop. Adding `tabindex` would *break* the experience for keyboard users by creating a dead stop.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\nThe dot has exactly **three mutually-exclusive states** (active, warning, error). There is no loading/expanded/selected/pressed/checked/busy state \u2014 it is a static value display, not a stateful control. Each state must be conveyed **both visually and programmatically**, with a **non-color** visual channel in addition to color.\n\nThe non-color *visual* differentiator (for color-blind and low-vision sighted users) and the *programmatic* text equivalent (for screen reader users) are two separate requirements; both are mandatory.\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Color (existing) | Non-color VISUAL indicator (required, WCAG 1.4.1) | Programmatic indicator | ARIA | WCAG |\n|-------|------------------|---------------------------------------------------|------------------------|------|------|\n| Active | Green | Text label \"Active\" (full mode) **and/or** a distinct icon glyph/shape \u2014 e.g. filled circle \u25cf, or check \u2713 \u2014 distinguishable by shape, not just hue | Text equivalent \"Active\" in accessibility tree | Full: `aria-hidden` dot + text sibling. Compact: `role=\"img\"` `aria-label=\"Active\"` | 1.4.1, 1.1.1 |\n| Warning | Yellow | Text label \"Warning\" **and/or** distinct shape \u2014 e.g. triangle \u25b2 or filled-but-different glyph | Text equivalent \"Warning\" | same as above with \"Warning\" | 1.4.1, 1.1.1 |\n| Error | Red | Text label \"Error\" **and/or** distinct shape \u2014 e.g. square \u25a0 or cross \u2715 | Text equivalent \"Error\" | same as above with \"Error\" | 1.4.1, 1.1.1 |\n\n**The decisive non-color requirement (WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color):** color must never be the *only* visual means of conveying the status. Two acceptable ways to satisfy this, in priority order:\n\n1. **Preferred \u2014 visible text label (full-label mode).** When a text label \"Active\"/\"Warning\"/\"Error\" is visible beside the dot, color is no longer the sole indicator: the word carries the meaning for *everyone*, including color-blind sighted users who never touch a screen reader. This is the strongest fix and should be the default mode.\n\n2. **Compact mode (text hidden) \u2014 add a shape/glyph difference.** When the design hides the label, the *visible* differentiation collapses back to color alone for sighted color-blind users \u2014 re-introducing the 1.4.1 failure for them even though screen reader users are covered by `aria-label`. To keep 1.4.1 satisfied in compact mode, the three dots must differ by **shape or glyph**, not only hue (e.g., \u25cf active, \u25b2 warning, \u2715 error; or distinct icons inside the dot). A screen-reader text equivalent alone does **not** satisfy 1.4.1 for a sighted dichromat looking at compact mode.\n\n> **Friction / honest flag for the design team:** The constraint \"dot shape and color system remain unchanged\" is in direct tension with WCAG 1.4.1 *in compact mode*. If all three dots are identical circles distinguished only by color, compact mode fails 1.4.1 for color-blind sighted users \u2014 `aria-label` does not rescue them because they are not using a screen reader. **This tension must be resolved before compact mode ships.** Options, cheapest first: (a) keep a minimal always-visible text label even in \"compact\" mode (e.g., a single letter or short word) \u2014 arguably defeats the point of compact mode; (b) differentiate the three statuses by **shape/glyph** in addition to color (recommended \u2014 preserves compactness, satisfies 1.4.1); (c) accept that compact mode is only offered where every viewer is guaranteed non-dichromat (not realistic for an internal ops tool). Recommendation: **(b)**. Surface this to design rather than silently shipping a 1.4.1 failure that automated tools won't catch.\n\n**No live region.** State is set at render time per row. `aria-live` is deliberately omitted (see Interaction Pattern Design).\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n### Color contrast \u2014 WCAG 1.4.11 Non-Text Contrast (the one that's easy to get wrong)\n\nThe dot is a **graphical object required to understand the content**, so WCAG 1.4.11 applies: it needs **\u2265 3:1 contrast against adjacent color(s).**\n\n**The common mistake to avoid (called out in the fixture):** measuring the dot against **white** only. The dot sits on real backgrounds: sidebar nav (often a tinted/dark panel), table rows (white *and* zebra-striped alternate-row gray, *and* hover state), and card headers (possibly tinted). The 3:1 ratio must hold against **every background the dot actually appears on**, not a hypothetical white.\n\n| Dot | Must be \u2265 3:1 against\u2026 | Check each |\n|---|---|---|\n| Green | white row bg, zebra-stripe gray row bg, row hover bg, sidebar panel bg, card header bg | All of them |\n| Yellow | (same list) | **Yellow is the highest risk** \u2014 a bright yellow dot on a white or light-gray row commonly measures < 3:1 and fails |\n| Red | (same list) | All of them |\n\n**Action for implementer:** Enumerate every distinct background the dot renders on. For each (dot color \u00d7 background) pair, verify \u2265 3:1 with a contrast tool. **Yellow-on-light is the most likely failure** and may require darkening the yellow (e.g., toward amber/`#B45309`-range) or adding a subtle border ring on the dot to create a contrasting edge. If the design team's exact hex values aren't provided in this plan, that is the **one open input required** \u2014 request the green/yellow/red hex values and the full background palette, then run the matrix. Do not assume the shipped colors pass; verify.\n\n> Note on 1.4.3 vs 1.4.11: **1.4.3 (text contrast, 4.5:1) does not apply to the dot** (it's not text). It *does* apply to the visible \"Active/Warning/Error\" **text labels** \u2014 those must meet 4.5:1 against their background like any body text. The dot is governed by 1.4.11 (3:1).\n\n### Windows High Contrast Mode / Forced Colors\n\nA dot drawn purely with `background-color` can **disappear** under Windows High Contrast Mode / `forced-colors: active`, because the OS replaces author background colors with system colors. Plan for this:\n- Test under `@media (forced-colors: active)`.\n- Because the **text equivalent** (visible label in full mode, `aria-label`/sr-only text in compact mode) is *not* color-dependent, the *meaning* survives forced-colors even if the dot's fill is flattened \u2014 this is a strong argument for the text-equivalent approach over a color-only fix.\n- Optionally use a `1px solid` border (system-color-aware) on the dot so its shape persists when the fill is overridden.\n\n### Other visual items\n- **Size / target:** the dot is non-interactive, so WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size (44\u00d744) **does not apply** \u2014 it is not a target. Do not inflate the dot to 44px; that would be over-engineering. (If the dot is ever wrapped to be independently clickable, that's a different component and 2.5.8 would apply to the clickable wrapper.)\n- **prefers-reduced-motion:** the dot is static; nothing to disable. (If a \"live/pulsing\" animated variant exists or is added, gate the animation behind `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` per WCAG 2.3.3 \u2014 but no animation is in scope now.)\n- **Zoom / reflow (1.4.10):** a small inline dot reflows trivially; no special handling.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\nThis is the heart of the fix.\n\n**Text alternative strategy (WCAG 1.1.1, 1.4.1):**\n\n- **Full-label mode:** the visible text label (\"Active\"/\"Warning\"/\"Error\") is the text alternative and the accessible status. The dot is **decorative duplication** \u2192 `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on the dot `<span>` (or `<svg>`). This prevents the **double-announcement** failure the fixture explicitly warns against (\"green circle Active\"). Verify the dot contributes *nothing* to the accessible name when a text sibling is present.\n\n- **Compact mode:** there is no visible text, so the dot must carry the name itself. **Pick exactly ONE mechanism** (do not stack both \u2014 that risks double-announcement):\n\n  **Recommended: `role=\"img\"` + `aria-label`** on the dot element.\n  ```\n  <span class=\"dot dot--green\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Active\"></span>\n  ```\n  - `role=\"img\"` tells AT \"this is a single meaningful graphic,\" and `aria-label` supplies its name \u2014 announced reliably as \"Active, image\" / \"Active, graphic\" across NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver.\n  - **Why this over the alternatives:**\n    - **vs. `title` attribute:** `title` produces a mouse tooltip and is **not reliably announced** by screen readers (JAWS/NVDA behavior varies; many users never get it; keyboard and touch users never see it). The fixture lists `title`-only as below-expectations. **Do not use `title` as the accessible name.**\n    - **vs. visually-hidden `<span>` text alone (no role):** also valid and robust, but then the dot `<span>` carries no role, and an empty styled `<span>` with `aria-hidden` would hide the very text you want read. The `role=\"img\"` + `aria-label` pattern is cleaner for a glyph-less colored dot. **Either is acceptable; choose `role=\"img\"`+`aria-label` for simplicity and pick one.**\n\n  **Acceptable alternative: visually-hidden text node** (if you prefer real text in the DOM, e.g., for easier testing or i18n string handling):\n  ```\n  <span class=\"dot dot--green\">\n    <span class=\"sr-only\">Active</span>\n  </span>\n  ```\n  with the dot `<span>` **not** `aria-hidden` (it must expose its child text). Use the standard clip technique below. Do **not** also add `aria-label` \u2014 that would override/duplicate the child text.\n\n- **Critical anti-pattern (fixture-flagged):** the accessible name must be the **semantic status**, never the visual artifact.\n  - WRONG: `aria-label=\"red dot\"`, `aria-label=\"green circle\"` \u2014 describes appearance, useless as status, and meaningless to someone who can't see \"red.\"\n  - RIGHT: `aria-label=\"Error\"` (or the product's term, e.g., \"Failing\").\n\n**The `.sr-only` / visually-hidden CSS technique (for compact mode and any hidden labels) \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1:**\nUse the well-established clip pattern that hides text **visually** while keeping it **in the accessibility tree**:\n```\n.sr-only {\n  position: absolute;\n  width: 1px; height: 1px;\n  padding: 0; margin: -1px;\n  overflow: hidden;\n  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);\n  clip-path: inset(50%);\n  white-space: nowrap;\n  border: 0;\n}\n```\n**Do NOT use `display: none` or `visibility: hidden` for the label** \u2014 those remove it from the accessibility tree entirely, re-creating the original \"screen reader gets nothing\" bug. The point of compact mode accessibility is *visually hidden, programmatically present.*\n\n**Language:** \"Active/Warning/Error\" inherit page `lang`; no per-part `lang` needed unless the product is localized (then the labels are translated strings, which is why a `label` prop / i18n key is preferable to hardcoded English).\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\nAutomated tools will **not** catch the core bug here. axe-core can flag a missing alt/name on `role=\"img\"`, but it **cannot** verify that \"Active\" is the *correct, meaningful* status, cannot detect the **double-announcement** in full mode, and cannot judge **1.4.1 compact-mode color-only** differentiation for dichromats. Manual + AT testing is mandatory.\n\n**1. Automated (axe-core / a11y-test skill):**\n- Run on **all three statuses \u00d7 both modes** (6 variants).\n- Confirms: `role=\"img\"` has an accessible name (compact mode); no empty/missing alt; text-label contrast (4.5:1) flagged if labels are too low-contrast.\n- Known gaps axe will miss (test manually): semantic correctness of the label, double-announcement, 1.4.11 dot-vs-background (axe checks text contrast well but graphical-object 1.4.11 coverage is partial), forced-colors behavior.\n\n**2. Contrast verification (WCAG 1.4.11) \u2014 manual, with a contrast tool:**\n- Build the matrix: each dot color \u00d7 each real background (white row, zebra gray row, hover, sidebar panel, card header). Confirm **\u2265 3:1** for every cell.\n- Confirm visible **text labels \u2265 4.5:1** (1.4.3) against their backgrounds.\n- Explicitly test **yellow** \u2014 highest failure risk.\n\n**3. Screen reader testing (the test that actually proves the fix):**\n- NVDA + Firefox/Chrome (Windows), JAWS + Chrome (Windows), VoiceOver + Safari (macOS).\n- **Full-label mode:** navigate to a row. Confirm AT announces the status **once** as text (\"Active\") \u2014 **not** \"green circle Active\" (double-announcement) and **not** just the dot with no status. This catches the missing `aria-hidden` regression.\n- **Compact mode:** navigate to a row with no visible label. Confirm AT announces \"Active\" (or product term) via the dot's `role=\"img\"`/sr-only text. Confirm it is **not** \"red dot,\" \"green,\" \"image,\" or silence.\n- Confirm the dot is **not** a tab stop (Tab through the page; the dot must be skipped).\n\n**4. Color Vision Deficiency check (1.4.1, sighted dichromats) \u2014 manual:**\n- View **compact mode** through a deuteranopia/protanopia simulator (browser devtools \"Emulate vision deficiencies,\" or Color Oracle).\n- Question: *with the text labels hidden, can the three statuses still be told apart?* If they're identical circles differing only in hue, this **fails** \u2192 the shape/glyph differentiation from the State Communication section is required. This is the test that exposes the design-constraint tension.\n\n**5. Windows High Contrast / forced-colors (the fixture's required test case):**\n- \"Change system color theme to high-contrast Windows \u2014 are status meanings still conveyed?\"\n- Enable Windows High Contrast Mode (or `@media (forced-colors: active)` in devtools).\n- Confirm: the **text equivalent** (visible label or AT name) still conveys status even if the dot's fill is overridden/flattened. Confirm the dot's shape persists if a border was added.\n\n**6. DOM verification (required \u2014 not just visual/unit):**\n- Inspect the **rendered DOM** for each mode and status. Confirm:\n  - Full mode: dot has `aria-hidden=\"true\"`; a real text node \"Active/Warning/Error\" is present as a sibling.\n  - Compact mode: dot has `role=\"img\"` + `aria-label=\"<status>\"` **OR** contains an `.sr-only` text node (exactly one mechanism, not both); dot is **not** `aria-hidden` in this case.\n  - No `tabindex` on the dot anywhere.\n  - `aria-label` value is the **status word**, never \"dot\"/\"circle\"/color name.\n\n**Acceptance criteria (must all pass):**\n- [ ] Every status, in every mode, exposes a correct text equivalent to NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver.\n- [ ] Full-label mode announces status **once** (no double-announcement).\n- [ ] Compact mode announces the **semantic status**, never the visual artifact.\n- [ ] No `title`-only accessible name anywhere.\n- [ ] Every (dot color \u00d7 background) pair \u2265 3:1 (1.4.11); yellow explicitly verified.\n- [ ] Compact mode distinguishes statuses by **more than color** for sighted dichromats (1.4.1), OR the design tension has been explicitly resolved/accepted by design with sign-off.\n- [ ] Status meaning survives Windows High Contrast Mode.\n- [ ] Dot is never focusable; never a tab stop.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Add semantic status + text equivalent to `StatusDot` (full-label and compact modes)\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `StatusDot.tsx` (the shipped component), `StatusDot.module.css` (or wherever dot styles live \u2014 add `.sr-only` if not already present), `StatusDot.test.tsx`.\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n```\n// Inputs: a semantic status (active|warning|error) and a mode (full|compact),\n// plus an optional product-specific label override.\n// Color is derived from status; the announced text is derived from status/label,\n// NEVER from the color name.\n\nFull-label mode (text sibling visible):\n  <span class=\"dot dot--{color}\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></span>\n  <span class=\"status-label\">{label}</span>     // e.g. \"Active\"\n\nCompact mode (no visible text) \u2014 choose ONE:\n  (A, recommended)\n  <span class=\"dot dot--{color}\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"{label}\"></span>\n  (B, alternative)\n  <span class=\"dot dot--{color}\"><span class=\"sr-only\">{label}</span></span>\n```\n\n**ARIA / attribute requirements:**\n- Full mode: `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on the dot \u2014 WCAG 1.1.1 / 4.1.2 (prevents double-announcement; dot is decorative when text sibling exists).\n- Compact mode (A): `role=\"img\"` \u2014 WCAG 1.1.1 (declares the graphic); `aria-label=\"{label}\"` \u2014 WCAG 1.1.1 / 1.4.1 (supplies the non-color text equivalent).\n- Compact mode (B): `.sr-only` text child, dot NOT `aria-hidden` \u2014 WCAG 1.3.1 / 1.4.1.\n- **No `tabindex`** anywhere \u2014 WCAG 2.1.1 / 2.4.3 (must not create a dead tab stop).\n- **No `title`** as the name mechanism.\n\n**Keyboard interactions:** None. The dot is not focusable. (Explicitly do not add any.)\n\n**Focus management:** None. (Explicitly do not add `tabindex`.)\n\n**State communication:** Map `active\u2192green/\"Active\"`, `warning\u2192yellow/\"Warning\"`, `error\u2192red/\"Error\"` (or product label override). One state per render; no live region.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Renders correct text equivalent for each of the 3 statuses, in both modes (DOM assertions, 6 cases).\n- Full mode: dot has `aria-hidden=\"true\"` AND a sibling text node with the label.\n- Compact mode: dot has `role=\"img\"`+`aria-label=\"{label}\"` (or `.sr-only` child) and is NOT `aria-hidden`.\n- `aria-label`/text equals the status word, not a color/shape word.\n- No `tabindex` rendered.\n- Screen reader smoke test (manual, recorded): single announcement in full mode; semantic announcement in compact mode.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.1.1 Non-text Content, 1.3.1 Info and Relationships, 1.4.1 Use of Color, 4.1.2 Name Role Value.\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Verify and (if needed) remediate dot contrast + compact-mode non-color differentiation\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint**\n\n**Files:** `StatusDot.module.css` (dot colors, optional border, optional shape/glyph per status), design-token source if colors are tokenized.\n\n**Work:**\n- Build the (dot color \u00d7 background) contrast matrix; verify **\u2265 3:1** everywhere (1.4.11). Remediate failures \u2014 likely **yellow**: darken toward amber and/or add a contrasting `1px` ring on the dot.\n- For **compact mode**, add a **non-color visual differentiator** (distinct shape/glyph per status) so dichromat sighted users can tell statuses apart without the text label (1.4.1). If design rejects this, escalate the tension (documented in State Communication) for explicit sign-off \u2014 do not silently ship a 1.4.1 failure.\n- Add `@media (forced-colors: active)` handling / border so the dot shape persists under Windows High Contrast.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Contrast matrix documented, every cell \u2265 3:1 (1.4.11); yellow explicitly verified.\n- Deuteranopia/protanopia simulation of compact mode: 3 statuses distinguishable without text.\n- Windows High Contrast / forced-colors: meaning still conveyed.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:** 1.4.1 Use of Color, 1.4.11 Non-Text Contrast.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus |\n|-----------|-----------|-------|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Task 1 | Text equivalent is the **semantic status**, not the visual artifact (\"Active\" not \"green dot\"). Full mode has `aria-hidden` on the dot (no double-announcement). Compact mode uses **exactly one** name mechanism (`role=\"img\"`+`aria-label` OR `.sr-only`, not both, never `title`). No `tabindex`. `.sr-only` uses clip, not `display:none`. DOM verified for all 6 variants. |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Task 2 | 1.4.11 verified against **every real background** (not just white); yellow specifically checked. Compact mode satisfies 1.4.1 for **sighted dichromats** via shape/glyph, or the design tension is explicitly resolved. Forced-colors behavior confirmed. No over-engineering (no live region, no focus management, no 44px inflation). |\n\n---\n\n### Contract Appendix (for spec-kitty-bridge WP translation)\n\n### Architecture Overview\nRemediate a shipped, color-only `StatusDot` so status is conveyed through a programmatic **text equivalent** in addition to color. The semantic status (active/warning/error) \u2014 not the color name \u2014 drives the announced text. Two render modes: **full-label** (visible text sibling carries meaning; dot `aria-hidden`) and **compact** (dot carries meaning via `role=\"img\"`+`aria-label`, or visually-hidden text). No interactivity, focus management, or live regions are introduced \u2014 the dot is a static image-role indicator. A separate contrast/shape pass satisfies 1.4.11 (3:1 vs. adjacent backgrounds) and keeps 1.4.1 satisfied for sighted dichromats in compact mode.\n\n### Implementation Tasks\n\n#### Task 1: Semantic status + text equivalent (full + compact modes)\nEstimated Effort: low \u2014 one shipped component (`StatusDot.tsx`), ~15 lines plus `.sr-only` CSS.\nDepends on: none.\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 1\nDOM assertions across 3 statuses \u00d7 2 modes (6 cases): correct text equivalent; full mode dot `aria-hidden` + text sibling; compact mode `role=\"img\"`+`aria-label` (or `.sr-only`) and not `aria-hidden`; label is the status word; no `tabindex`. Manual SR smoke test (NVDA/JAWS/VoiceOver): single announcement (full), semantic announcement (compact). axe-core on all 6 variants. WCAG 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 1.4.1, 4.1.2.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 1\nEvery status \u00d7 mode exposes a correct semantic text equivalent to NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver; full mode announces once (no double-announcement); compact mode announces the semantic status (never \"red dot\"/color/shape); exactly one name mechanism in compact mode; no `title`-only name; dot never focusable.\n\n#### Task 2: Contrast + compact-mode non-color differentiation\nEstimated Effort: low\u2013medium \u2014 depends on how many backgrounds the dot appears on and whether yellow fails (likely).\nDepends on: Task 1 (and design input: green/yellow/red hex values + full background palette).\n\n#### Test Strategy for Task 2\nContrast matrix (each dot color \u00d7 each real background) all \u2265 3:1 (1.4.11), yellow explicitly verified; text labels \u2265 4.5:1 (1.4.3); deuteranopia/protanopia simulation of compact mode shows 3 distinguishable statuses (1.4.1); Windows High Contrast / `forced-colors: active` preserves meaning. WCAG 1.4.1, 1.4.11.\n\n#### Acceptance Criteria for Task 2\nAll (dot \u00d7 background) pairs \u2265 3:1; yellow passes; compact mode distinguishable by more than color OR design tension signed off; status survives Windows High Contrast.\n\n### Failure Modes\n- **Double-announcement** (\"green circle Active\") \u2014 full mode dot missing `aria-hidden=\"true\"`.\n- **Visual-artifact name** \u2014 `aria-label=\"red dot\"` instead of `aria-label=\"Error\"`; meaningless and color-dependent.\n- **`title`-only name** \u2014 tooltip not reliably announced; never read by some ATs, never by keyboard/touch.\n- **`display:none`/`visibility:hidden` on the compact-mode label** \u2014 removes it from the accessibility tree, re-creating the original \"screen reader gets nothing\" bug.\n- **Stacking both mechanisms** in compact mode (`role=\"img\"`+`aria-label` *and* `.sr-only` child) \u2014 risks duplicate announcement.\n- **Contrast vs. white only** \u2014 passes on white, fails on zebra/hover/sidebar/card backgrounds; yellow especially.\n- **Compact-mode 1.4.1 gap** \u2014 identical circles differing only by hue; `aria-label` covers screen readers but NOT sighted dichromats; shape/glyph differentiation missing.\n- **Over-engineering** \u2014 adding `tabindex`, `aria-live`, focus management, or 44px target sizing to a static indicator; each introduces new defects (dead tab stops, spurious announcements) and is explicitly out of scope.\n- **Hardcoded \"Active/Warning/Error\"** when product context uses different terminology (Passing/Degraded/Failing, Online/Away/Offline) \u2014 announced status mismatches visible context.\n",
